================================================================================
  1. VOICE & CONTENT
================================================================================

PassTo speaks TO a nurse, not at her. Plain. Direct. No jargon. No exclamation
points. Numbers and dates beat adjectives. Verbs beat nouns. Respectful of
her time and her expertise.

VOICE RULES
  - Second person. "Your license is verified." Never "Users can verify..."
  - Active voice, present tense. "Verifies in seconds."
  - Plain English. No "leverage," "streamline," "solution," "ecosystem."
  - No hedging. "Expires in 47 days. Renew now." Not "may be expiring soon."
  - No exclamation points. Confidence doesn't shout.
  - No emoji in product UI.
  - Sentence case for buttons and headings. Title Case only for proper nouns
    and the wordmark.

CASING
  - Sentence case in headings/buttons: "Get your Pass," "How it works"
  - Proper-noun "Pass" when referring to the artifact: "your Pass"
  - "PassTo" is one word, Pass + To, "To" rendered in verified-600 on light
    and verified-400 on dark.
  - State names on credentials: UPPERCASE ("CALIFORNIA," "NEW YORK")
  - Body dates: "14 May 2026". Pass dates: "14 MAY 2026" (uppercase, mono)

ON-BRAND SAMPLES
  - "Your license is verified and live."
  - "Expires in 47 days. Renew now."
  - "Tap to share. They'll see it live."
  - "Three taps. One pocket."
  - "PassTo re-verifies your license every 24 hours."

OFF-BRAND (DO NOT WRITE)
  - "Awesome! Your amazing credential is all set!"   — too eager, emoji
  - "Don't forget — your license might expire soon!" — hedging
  - "Leverage PassTo to seamlessly transmit..."      — enterprise jargon

WHAT WE DO NOT WRITE
  - Wellness-app language ("Take a deep breath," "Your journey")
  - Marketing pitch ("Revolutionary," "Game-changing")
  - Apologetic UI ("Oops!" "Whoops!" "Sorry...")
  - Cute system anthropomorphism ("I'll just be a moment...")
  - Long hedged FAQs


